    "For instance, Taleb et al. (2023) presented and deployed an AI-empowered anomaly diagnosis mechanism to the high-dimensional data gathered from different 5G network components.",
    "Another similar study was Saeed et al. (2023) where the authors proposed an AI-driven approach for anomaly detection in IoT networks, relying solely on unsupervised learning to identify anomalies in resource-constrained IoT devices.",
    "Researchers have developed novel algorithms and approaches to improve the ability of AI to detect anomalies in telecom infrastructure.",
    "Among these approaches, Generative Adversarial Networks (GANs) have emerged as an effective tool for a variety of anomaly detection applications (Goodfellow et al. 2014).",
    "As summarized in Table 3, GANs, or Generative Adversarial Networks, are inspired by the two-person zero-sum game from game theory."
